
{
  "documentMetadata": {
    "title": "Granuloma Inguinale (Donovanosis)",
    "lastUpdated": "2024-04-01",
    "sourceFile": "Granuloma inguinale (Donovanosis).pdf"
  },
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Clinical Setting"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "Granuloma inguinale or Donovanosis",
        "Painless, progressive ulcerative disease without regional lymphadenopathy.",
        "Highly vascular (beefy red) lesions that bleed easily.",
        "Rare in US; common in Southeast Asia (India), South America & Southern Africa. Was endemic in Australia, but now relatively rare."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Etiologies"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "Klebsiella granulomatis (formerly Calymmatobacterium granulomatis)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Diagnosis"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "Culture of causative organism is difficult and unreliable.",
        "Darkfield microscopy; Donovan Bodies organisms visible in macrophages using Wright-Giemsa on biopsy.",
        "PCR techniques for diagnosis also available in some labs."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Primary Regimens"
    },
    {
      "type": "drugRegimen",
      "regimenData": {
        "intent": "treatment",
        "components": [
          {
            "drug": "Azithromycin",
            "dose": "1 gm",
            "route": "po",
            "frequency": "once weekly (or 500 mg daily)",
            "duration": "x at least 3 weeks (or until resolved)"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "If no evident improvement in the first few days, some experts add Gentamicin 1 mg/kg IV q8h."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Alternative Regimens"
    },
    {
      "type": "drugRegimen",
      "regimenData": {
        "intent": "treatment",
        "components": [
          {
            "drug": "Doxycycline",
            "dose": "100 mg",
            "route": "po",
            "frequency": "bid",
            "duration": "x 3 weeks"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "drugRegimen",
      "regimenData": {
        "intent": "treatment",
        "components": [
          {
            "drug": "TMP-SMX",
            "dose": "DS",
            "route": "po",
            "frequency": "q12h",
            "duration": "x 3 weeks"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "drugRegimen",
      "regimenData": {
        "intent": "treatment",
        "components": [
          {
            "drug": "Ciprofloxacin",
            "dose": "750 mg",
            "route": "po",
            "frequency": "bid",
            "duration": "x 3 weeks"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "drugRegimen",
      "regimenData": {
        "intent": "treatment",
        "components": [
          {
            "drug": "Erythromycin",
            "dose": "500 mg",
            "route": "po",
            "frequency": "qid",
            "duration": "x 3 weeks"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Antimicrobial Stewardship"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "Duration: clinical response is usually seen in 1 week. Treat until all lesions are healed. This may take 4 weeks.",
        "Treatment failures and recurrence seen with Doxycycline and TMP-SMX."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Comments"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "Sexual partners within 60 days should be evaluated. Role of empiric therapy in asymptomatic contacts unclear.",
        "Screen all patients for HIV.",
        "Treatment is no different for HIV patients with Granuloma inguinale.",
        "Relapse can occur 6-18 months after apparently effective therapy.",
        "See 2021 CDC STD Guidelines: MMWR Recomm Rep 70 (RR-4):1 2021 or 2016 European Guideline on Donovanosis Int J STD AIDS 27:605, 2016.",
        "Review non syphilis non HSV genital ulcers: Infect Dis Clin North Am 37:369 2023."
      ]
    }
  ]
}
